description:
In this video, I'm sharing my personal goals for 2025 and the system I've developed to actually stay consistent with them. As a software engineer, I believe in creating sustainable systems - whether that's for coding or building habits. I break down my major goals including developing an MVP for my side project, setting up a home server with my Raspberry Pi, and maintaining healthy habits like daily stretching and green smoothies.

Want to turn your goals into consistent habits? I share four tips that have helped me stay on track, both in my software development journey and personal growth. Whether you're a developer looking to balance coding projects with healthy habits, or just someone wanting to make lasting changes, these practical strategies will help you build a sustainable routine.

Timestamps:
00:00 Welcome back!
00:39 Code side project MVP
01:48 Host website from Raspberry Pi
02:42 Consistent gym routine
03:45 Daily stretching
04:52 Weekly green smoothies
06:00 Monthly audio book
06:43 Power of 30 minutes 
08:21 Dont think, just do
09:55 Motivation comes from doing
11:03 Set your environment for change
12:30 See you soon!

Join me for fun moments away from my keyboard from daily adventures to life in Sweden: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2Bm4qXVUx9Md-hmHz3WuXw/join

#softwareengineer #consistency #developerlife

comments.text: Vanessa, new subscriber, you make amazing insightful videos.  A word on "green smoothies".  My personal study obsession is metabolism and nutritional health/longevity.  Nothing wrong with some "green" stuff in the diet (I include some carefully selected dark green vegetables in my diet for a bit of fiber for gut health and necessary magnesium which most of us are deficient in), but you have to be careful.  Do some study on "oxalates" which are crystal-like components in many plants that are meant to be a natural "defense mechanism" the plants use to passively survive as a species by poisoning insects or animals that would eat them, or interrupting the reproductive process of those insects or animals.  Oxalates can cause kidney stones or build up in many other places in the body causing great trouble.  Some vegetables are benign or have negligible levels of oxalates, others (like spinach and Swiss) chard have extremely high levels of them and should be avoided.  Oxalates can be found in other foods like nuts and seeds, but they are most prevalent in certain green veggies.  The cruciferous vegetables from the cabbage family and usually good for us, as they were growing above ground when we were "cave people" long ago so it is likely we reached down to grab them occasionally and munch on them, so our metabolism evolved to handle them occasionally (but not as our complete diet).  One could easily come up with a chart of veggies with oxalate content from "least to most" and prioritize those with the least content, the research and data is available on the web.  The cruciferous veggies also  contain low levels of sulfur compounds which have positive health effects for us (study "sulforaphane") such as inducing our body to be in an "anti cancer" mode.  See "Dr. Rhonda Patrick" videos about this.  For the study of "oxalates", you can look up interviews by "Sally Norton", she is the foremost expert on oxalate sickness.  Don't be indiscriminate with green stuff, our digestive tract is not the same as animals such as rabbits (they have a "coecum" which we don't), "ruminant" animals such as cows/goats/sheep (they have regurgitating multi-fermentation-chambers) and we don't have the huge fiber-churning large intestine that gorillas do.  Our digestive tract is actually almost identical to canines and felines with a very long small intestine and quite short fiber-processing large intestine.  In short, our bodies "can handle" some fibrous veggie matter in a pinch, or to fulfill some mineral/vitamin needs, but one must not overdo it.   A hint for you in selecting plant foods to include in the diet...try to determine if that plant "wanted to be eaten by us" or not.  Berries for example, propagate themselves by making themselves attractive to be eaten by birds and animals (they are usually sweet and very colorful) so that the animal will later "deposit" the seeds in them within their excrement in a different region, along with a nice little pile of "fertilizer" to get them started growing.  Hence most berries and fruits are generally benign for us to eat, contain vitamins, minerals, carotenes (antioxidant and eye health) as well as some gut-health fiber.  The berry/fruit plants "don't want to hurt us" as a species because they essentially believe we are "doing them a favor" to help them thrive as a species.  We can't survive on berries and fruits alone though, too much sugar, that's a whole other discussion.  Simply put we don't have the metabolism genes or Pancreas design that tree monkeys have.  They can munch on sugar/carb laden fruits/dates/figs all day and not get diabetes (we will).  Also do some study on "lectins", which are another plant-defense-mechanism, they are quite harmful to health both physical and neurological (recently being linked to Parkinsons' and dementia).  Also study the negative effects of chemicals in "Nightshade" type vegetables.  About gut health, a healthy microbiome is bacterial (and benign yeast) colonies consuming not only fibers but also fats and proteins (contrary to popular thought), and as their waste product they produce short-chain-saturated fats (carbon chains of 2, 3, 4 etc), which remarkably the intestines/colon use as a "locally produced energy source" (not received through the blood stream) to power the digestive function and repair of the digestive tract lining cells.  I am currently obsessed with the importance of these 'short chain saturated fats' (butyrate especially) in overall health and longevity.  Most of the healthy, long-lived cultures around the world have higher amounts of "fermented foods" (primitive mans' original way of preserving food for later use) in their diet which would contain high amounts of "ready made" short chain saturated fats in them, just like the ones produced by our gut bacteria, so "fermented foods" (yogurt, kefir, sauerkraut, kimchi and other lactobacillus fermented veggies) could be considered a good health/longevity "hack", giving you a boost of the beneficial SCSF's in addition to those your microbiome is making.  Anyone with a poor microbiome health should definitely be consuming some "live" fermented foods (must be the refrigerated kind at the store, as all "room temperature jars" of fermented foods on the store shelves are boiled in the canning process and are "dead" in terms of the probiotic bacteria content although some SCSFs might still be there.  A lot of "store shelf jar" sauerkraut is not fermented though, it's just "pickled" with vinegar for fast production).  BTW, fermented foods are also high in "K" vitamins, very important for health, especially K2 which is important for calcium mobilization in the body, keeping it from lingering in the bloodstream and sticking to blood vessel linings and heart valves, thereby reducing incidence of heart problems, clots and hardened arteries).  The microbiome bacteria as well as fermenting bacteria in fermented foods produce the K vitamins in their waste product just like the SCSFs. .

comments.text:
Our brain is know nothing about motivation. 
The brain saves energy on everything and is ready to spend it only on satisfying basic needs, but it can be deceived.
So this is a short advise on how to accomplish a feat:
1. Create an informational dominant or lets say - focus (start reading, watching videos, researching information).
2. Inventory the current situation (it's difficult or even impossible to do this alone; ask others for feedback, have them tell you what you can do, what you have, and where your strengths lie).
3. Begin.


The main point here is to have a clear view and an informational dominant in the brain before starting any action, in this case the brain will be the best assistant and will not resist.
